 longDescShanghai: "<p>Shanghai, a global financial hub, is a city of superlatives. Its futuristic skyline, dominated by the Shanghai Tower and the Oriental Pearl TV Tower, is a sight to behold.</p><p>Stroll along the Bund to admire the colonial-era architecture, explore the trendy boutiques and art galleries in the French Concession, or find tranquility in the classical Yu Garden. Shanghai is a testament to China's rapid development and a must-visit for any traveler.</p>",
 longDescXian: "<p>Xi'an is one of the oldest cities in China and the eastern terminus of the Silk Road. Its most famous attraction is the Terracotta Army, a vast collection of life-sized terracotta sculptures depicting the armies of Qin Shi Huang, the first Emperor of China.</p><p>The city itself is surrounded by a well-preserved ancient city wall, which you can cycle on for incredible views. Don't miss the Muslim Quarter for a vibrant culinary experience.</p>",
 longDescGuilin: "<p>Guilin's landscape is the stuff of classic Chinese paintings. Located in Southern China, it is world-renowned for its otherworldly karst topography.</p><p>The best way to experience its beauty is by taking a cruise down the Li River, where you'll see limestone peaks, bamboo groves, and tranquil villages. You can also explore the Reed Flute Cave, a natural limestone cave with impressive stalactites and stalagmites illuminated by colorful lights.</p>",
 longDescZhangjiajie: "<p>Zhangjiajie is famous for its towering pillar-like sandstone formations set within a UNESCO-listed national park – an otherworldly landscape perfect for hiking and photography.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li><strong>Zhangjiajie National Forest Park</strong> – home to the famous quartz-sandstone pillars.</li><li><strong>Avatar Hallelujah Mountains</strong> – scenic viewpoints inspired cinematic landscapes.</li><li><strong>Glass Bridge (Zhangjiajie Grand Canyon)</strong> – a thrilling suspended walkway with dramatic views.</li></ul>",
 longDescJiuzhaigou: "<p>Jiuzhaigou is renowned for its vivid turquoise lakes, multi-tiered waterfalls and pristine alpine valleys – a scenic gem in Sichuan province.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li><strong>Rize Valley</strong> – colorful lakes and clear water reflections.</li><li><strong>Shuzheng Valley</strong> – classic views of layered waterfalls.</li><li><strong>Hiking & Photography</strong> – boardwalk trails provide easy access to viewpoints.</li></ul>",
 longDescYangtze: "<p>The Yangtze is China's longest river, famous for the dramatic Three Gorges and popular river cruises that combine scenery with cultural visits.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li><strong>Three Gorges</strong> – steep-sided gorges carved by the river offering spectacular views.</li><li><strong>Yangtze Cruises</strong> – multi-day cruise options between Chongqing and Yichang.</li><li><strong>Cultural stops</strong> – riverside towns, temples and local markets.</li></ul>",
 longDescIching: "<p>The <strong>I Ching</strong> (also written <em>iching</em>, Chinese: <strong>易经</strong>) – literally the <em>Book of Changes</em> – is one of the oldest Chinese classics. It combines cosmology, philosophy and a system of 64 hexagrams used historically for divination and decision-making.</p><h3>History & structure</h3><p>The iching developed over millennia. Each of its 64 hexagrams is formed from six lines (broken or unbroken). Traditional commentaries – the Ten Wings – expanded the text into a rich philosophical work used by scholars and sages.</p><h3>How iching divination works</h3><p>Modern iching methods use coins or yarrow stalk techniques to generate a hexagram. Interpreting the iching hexagram involves reading its meaning, line transformations, and how it relates to your question.</p><h3>Why read the I Ching today?</h3><ul><li><strong>Philosophical insight:</strong> iching offers frameworks for change and decision-making.</li><li><strong>Cultural context:</strong> Understanding 易经 deepens appreciation for Chinese thought, history and literature.</li><li><strong>Practical uses:</strong> meditation, creative prompts, and reflective decision processes.</li></ul><h3>Further reading & resources</h3><p>Recommended translations and commentaries include works by Richard Wilhelm (translated by Cary F. Baynes), and modern commentaries that explain iching hexagrams in contemporary terms.</p><h3>Learn more</h3><p>If you are visiting China and interested in cultural tours, ask local museums or cultural centers about lectures and exhibits related to I Ching and Chinese classical philosophy.</p>",
